\f0\b\fs54 \cf0 Chocolate Mint Chip Ice Cream Pie\
\pard\pardeftab720\sl240\ql\qnatural

\f1\fs34 \cf2 Serves:  
\b0 \cf0 Makes 1 ice cream pie\
\
\pard\pardeftab720\sl320\ql\qnatural

\f0\b\fs44 \cf0 Ingredients\
\pard\tx220\tx720\pardeftab720\li720\fi-720\sl400\ql\qnatural
\ls1\ilvl0
\f1\b0\fs42 \cf0 {\listtext	\'95	}2 cups heavy cream\
{\listtext	\'95	}1 cup whole {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "http://www.foodterms.com/encyclopedia/milk/index.html"}}{\fldrslt \cf2 milk}}\
{\listtext	\'95	}3/4 cup packed fresh {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "http://www.foodterms.com/encyclopedia/mint/index.html"}}{\fldrslt \cf2 mint}} leaves\
{\listtext	\'95	}4 egg yolks\
{\listtext	\'95	}1/2 cup sugar\
{\listtext	\'95	}2 tablespoons mint {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "http://www.foodterms.com/encyclopedia/liqueur/index.html"}}{\fldrslt \cf2 liqueur}} (recommended: creme de menthe)\
{\listtext	\'95	}3 ounces semisweet chocolate {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "http://www.foodterms.com/encyclopedia/chips/index.html"}}{\fldrslt \cf2 chips}}, or coarsely chopped chocolate bar (about 1/2 cup)\
{\listtext	\'95	}Chocolate {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "http://www.foodterms.com/encyclopedia/cookie/index.html"}}{\fldrslt \cf2 Cookie}} Crust, recipe follows\
\pard\pardeftab720\sl320\ql\qnatural

\f0\b\fs44 \cf0 Directions\
\pard\pardeftab720\sl400\sa140\ql\qnatural

\f1\b0\fs42 \cf0 In a medium {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "http://www.foodterms.com/encyclopedia/saucepan/index.html"}}{\fldrslt \cf2 saucepan}}, bring the cream, milk, and mint to a gentle {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "http://www.foodterms.com/encyclopedia/boil/index.html"}}{\fldrslt \cf2 boil}}. Remove from the heat.\
In a bowl, whisk together the egg yolks and sugar until thick. {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "http://www.foodterms.com/encyclopedia/whisk/index.html"}}{\fldrslt \cf2 Whisk}} 1 cup of the hot cream into the egg mixture. In a slow, steady stream, gradually add the egg mixture to the pan of hot cream. Cook over moderately low heat, stirring occasionally, until the mixture thickens enough to coat the back of a spoon and reaches 170 degrees F on an instant-read thermometer, 3 to 5 minutes.\
Remove the pan from the heat and strain the mixture into a clean bowl through a fine mesh {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "http://www.foodterms.com/encyclopedia/strainer/index.html"}}{\fldrslt \cf2 strainer}}. Pour into a container and cover with waxed paper or {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "http://www.foodterms.com/encyclopedia/plastic-wrap/index.html"}}{\fldrslt \cf2 plastic wrap}}, pressing down against the surface to keep a {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "http://www.foodterms.com/encyclopedia/skin/index.html"}}{\fldrslt \cf2 skin}} from forming. Chill in the refrigerator for at least 2 hours.\
When cold, stir in the mint liqueur and {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "http://www.foodterms.com/encyclopedia/chocolate/index.html"}}{\fldrslt \cf2 chocolate}} chips. Pour into the bowl of an ice cream machine, and {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "http://www.foodterms.com/encyclopedia/churn/index.html"}}{\fldrslt \cf2 churn}} and freeze according to manufacturer's instructions. When the ice cream has come together, transfer to the chocolate cookie crust and {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "http://www.foodterms.com/encyclopedia/finish/index.html"}}{\fldrslt \cf2 finish}} the ice cream pie, or transfer to an airtight container and place in the freezer until ready to use.\
To Assemble Ice Cream Pie: Place the piecrust in the freezer for at least 1 hour. Remove the {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "http://www.foodterms.com/encyclopedia/ice-cream/index.html"}}{\fldrslt \cf2 ice cream}} from the freezer and let sit at room temperature until soft enough to spread, 5 to 10 minutes.\
Remove the crust from the freezer and unwrap. Transfer the ice cream to the piecrust, filling to the top, and smooth with a {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "http://www.foodterms.com/encyclopedia/spatula/index.html"}}{\fldrslt \cf2 spatula}} or the back of a spoon. Place in the freezer until firm, and serve.\
\pard\pardeftab720\sl320\ql\qnatural

\f0\b\fs44 \cf0 Chocolate Cookie Crust:\
\pard\tx220\tx720\pardeftab720\li720\fi-720\sl400\ql\qnatural
\ls2\ilvl0
\f1\b0\fs42 \cf0 {\listtext	\'95	}1/2 cup {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "http://www.foodterms.com/encyclopedia/graham-cracker/index.html"}}{\fldrslt \cf2 graham cracker}} crumbs\
{\listtext	\'95	}3/4 cup finely ground chocolate sandwich cookies (NOTE: chocolate cookie only, cream {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "http://www.foodterms.com/encyclopedia/stuffing/index.html"}}{\fldrslt \cf2 stuffing}} removed)\
{\listtext	\'95	}4 tablespoons melted unsalted butter\
{\listtext	\'95	}2 tablespoons {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "http://www.foodterms.com/encyclopedia/sugar/index.html"}}{\fldrslt \cf2 sugar}}\
{\listtext	\'95	}1 egg white*\
\pard\pardeftab720\sl400\sa140\ql\qnatural
\cf0 *RAW EGG WARNING\
Food Network Kitchens suggest caution in consuming raw and lightly-cooked eggs due to the slight risk of {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "http://www.foodterms.com/encyclopedia/salmonella/index.html"}}{\fldrslt \cf2 Salmonella}} or other food-borne illness. To reduce this risk, we recommend you use only fresh, properly-refrigerated, clean, grade A or AA {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "http://www.foodterms.com/encyclopedia/eggs/index.html"}}{\fldrslt \cf2 eggs}} with intact shells, and avoid contact between the yolks or whites and the {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "http://www.foodterms.com/encyclopedia/shell/index.html"}}{\fldrslt \cf2 shell}}.\
Preheat the oven to 375 degrees F.\
In a bowl, combine all the ingredients in a bowl, except the egg white, and {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "http://www.foodterms.com/encyclopedia/blend/index.html"}}{\fldrslt \cf2 blend}} with a {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "http://www.foodterms.com/encyclopedia/mixer/index.html"}}{\fldrslt \cf2 mixer}}. Transfer to a 9-inch pie pan and spread across the bottom and up the sides using your fingers. Place another 9-inch {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "http://www.foodterms.com/encyclopedia/pie-pans-tins-plates/index.html"}}{\fldrslt \cf2 pie pan}} on top and firmly press against the contours of the pan to pack the crust down onto the pan. (Some of the filling may spill over the edges of the pan.)\
Bake until golden, 10 to 15 minutes. Remove from the oven and cool. Brush the {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "http://www.foodterms.com/encyclopedia/crust/index.html"}}{\fldrslt \cf2 crust}} with the egg white. Refrigerate before using.\
Yield: 1 (9-inch) crust\
